<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-of-heptagons" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Heptagons</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_76z7xc3x">
            <p xml:id="auto_g29lv970">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_xn0d0n2c">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_tboptwuj">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_oc09gqld">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8nux2ecm">
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ze4lz6ee">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_un7kmgo0">
                        Work out the area of regular heptagon and octagon. Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5fqbd6gh" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_i3erqrpi">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_usvhs9zg" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_p563mo9z">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5p6u4l1i" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_a4s9oimp"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jun2dfnc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_y1q3jtt3">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define the properties of a regular heptagon, including that it has 7 sides, the sum of interior angles is <m>900^\circ</m>, and the area can be found by dividing it into 7 congruent triangles.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_fjqcv35p">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3kw76kgv">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of a regular heptagon by dividing it into 7 congruent triangles and applying the formula <m>A = \frac{1}{2}ab\sin\theta</m> where <m>\theta = \frac{360^\circ}{7} \approx 51.43^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_wljyto8h">
                        <p xml:id="auto_mtp853cu">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply the heptagon area formula to solve real-world problems involving heptagonal structures such as coins, logos, and architectural designs.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_dut8sihb">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-heptagons.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_kht8z0ta">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-heptagons.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_v9r21b3w">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_f4662gxq">
            <alert>Anchor Activity:</alert> Constructing a Regular Heptagon
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_23swx2oe">
            Students work in groups of 3–5 to construct a regular heptagon using compass, ruler, and protractor. Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to use the tools correctly.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_f0vskw6t">
            <alert>Teacher Prompting Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tuoo2h6i">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_3d6bj6o4">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7icxqn3w"><q>What do you notice about the angles?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pfbb98ch">
                    <p xml:id="auto_v4as19v0"><q>How many sides does your polygon have?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7jgcsza0">
                    <p xml:id="auto_01xiv322"><q>Can you find the sum of the interior angles?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pw6pt7fl">
            <alert>For struggling groups:</alert> Draw the first angle together. Make sure it is <m>51.43^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_v2ir8k24">
            <alert>For early finishers:</alert> <q>Can you find the measure of one interior angle? Can you find heptagons in real life?</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dbntyntv">
            <alert>Expected Outcome:</alert> Students should articulate that a heptagon has seven sides and the sum of interior angles is <m>900^\circ</m>. Identify 2–3 groups with accurate constructions to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_2jhnhxca">
         A heptagon is a seven-sided polygon. It has seven edges and seven vertices.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="auto_v4r8tqt9">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_tch7gsnv">
                Constructing a Regular Heptagon
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qck2wk9n">
                Working in groups of 3-5 students.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mxx424b4">
                <m>\textbf{Materials needed:}</m>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_apvcsynr">Compass</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6z5b4mcx">Ruler</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pw8g6ef3">Protractor</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_cpd73xuj">Pencil</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_c2nvbtxx">Eraser</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xx8c8jqj">Graph paper (optional)</li>
            </ul>
            <p xml:id="auto_rjo6dr0x">
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_7cvrpd7g">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4fj095l5">
                            Draw a Circle
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_h0sfj658">Place the compass pointer on the paper and draw a circle of any radius.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ruhjyfd0">Mark the center (O) of the circle.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_i6y5g8ek">
                        <p xml:id="auto_d47he4ao">
                            Draw a Horizontal Diameter
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_527hz48d">Use the ruler to draw a straight line through the center (O), creating a diameter.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_njh9qbo8">Label the first point P1 on the circumference.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_rxaolbea">
                        <p xml:id="auto_nafdewca">
                            Divide the Circle into Seven Equal Parts
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wcjm5p1y">Use a protractor to measure angles of <m>\frac{360^\circ}{7} \approx 51.43^\circ</m> from point P1.</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_6hl1ngl5">Mark each point on the circumference as P2, P3, P4, and so on, until you have seven points.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_wpd4fbk8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_pjjmq5wp">
                            Connect the Points
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_10xluark">Using the ruler, connect the points P1, P2, P3, P4, P5, P6, and P7 to form the heptagon.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Teaching and Learning</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_0wqis0k4">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qdf2zff2">
            After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalize the properties of a regular heptagon and the area formula.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wqs5u446">
            Direct students to the Key Takeaway section in their textbooks. Walk through the properties, emphasizing:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_p2ky4cdl">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_6s8n1f08">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zz9byzda">The sum of interior angles formula: <m>(n-2) \times 180^\circ</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6mkqh5l6">
                    <p xml:id="auto_fqez73lf">A regular heptagon can be divided into 7 congruent triangles by drawing lines from the centre to each vertex.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yx2xtbi2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_f3bb5uyc">Area of one triangle <m>= \frac{1}{2}ab\sin\theta</m> where <m>\theta = \frac{360^\circ}{7} \approx 51.43^\circ</m></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vtn79s1i">
            <alert>Common Misconceptions to Address:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Misconception</cell>
                <cell>Clarification</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>All polygons have the same interior angle sum</cell>
                <cell>No, the sum depends on the number of sides: <m>(n-2) \times 180^\circ</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Multiplying side length by 7 gives the area</cell>
                <cell>No, that gives the perimeter. Use the triangle method for area</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Exterior angle equals the interior angle</cell>
                <cell>No, they are supplementary: interior <m>+</m> exterior <m>= 180^\circ</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>A heptagon is the same as a hexagon</cell>
                <cell>No, a hexagon has 6 sides while a heptagon has 7 sides</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </axiom>

<insight xml:id="auto_sgn7e6c5">
    <p xml:id="auto_upizzgj7">
        <m>\textbf{Properties of a Regular Heptagon.}</m>.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li xml:id="auto_q3prpvst">
            <p xml:id="auto_bcfthhz4">
                Sum of interior angles = <m> (n-2) \times 180^\circ</m>. Where n is the number of sides.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_2na8qq4j">
                <p xml:id="auto_a6qqcvxy">
                    Example for a Heptagon (7-sided polygon).
                </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_uzzjhs97">
            <p xml:id="auto_gn408ggi">
        <me>
          (n-2) \times 180^\circ  
        </me>
        <me>
            (7-2) \times 180^\circ = 900^\circ
        </me>      
    </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_kwseb2iq">
            <p xml:id="auto_9lq8oxr2">
       Sum of exterior angles of any <m>\textbf{polygon(regular or irregular)}</m> is always equal to <m>360^\circ</m> for both regular and irregular polygons.
    </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_k5krfp8j">
            <p xml:id="auto_mtfrny3n">
        Each Interior and Exterior Angle (Regular Polygon Only)
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sercziiw">
                <me>
                \textbf{Each Interior Angle (for a regular polygon):}    
                </me>
                <me>
                    Interior Angle = \frac{(n-2) \times 180^\circ}{n}
                </me>
                <me>
                    \textbf{Each Exterior Angle (for a regular polygon):}
                </me>
                <me>
                    Exterior Angle = \frac{360^ \circ}{n}
                </me>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_cm7mx8x2">
            <p xml:id="auto_y68tru2m">
            Example for a Regular Heptagon:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hte6s0kl">
                <me>
                    \textbf{Each Interior Angle} = \frac{900}{7}
                </me>
                <me>
                    = 128.57^ \circ
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7ypera5o">
                <me>
                    \textbf{Each Exterior Angle} = \frac{360}{7}
                </me>
                <me>
                    =51.43^ \circ
                </me>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p xml:id="auto_azw4ftgh">
        <m>\textbf{Study Questions}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_mtrdjlpx">
        <ol marker="(i)">
            <li xml:id="auto_0kkz5f1x">What is the sum of all interior angles of a heptagon?</li>
            <li xml:id="auto_jl58upfs">How do we calculate the measure of one interior angle of a regular heptagon?</li>
            <li xml:id="auto_gsr5hsgj">Can you find heptagons in real life?</li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    
</insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_158v6qby">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8rgp78cn">
            Work through the first example as a class, then allow students to attempt the second example independently or in pairs.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ft562wdf">
            <alert>Guiding Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hje982c0">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_29wzht37">
                    <p xml:id="auto_edioghmz">Remind students to identify how many triangles are formed (7 for a heptagon).</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_82o7kcw9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_d3ntl4f9">Ensure students use the correct central angle: <m>\frac{360^\circ}{7} \approx 51.43^\circ</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jt5psgn8">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7yn8djan">Check that students multiply the area of one triangle by 7 to get the total area.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_su2co55q">
        <statement>
            <sidebyside>
             <p xml:id="auto_loy269gt">
                A regular heptagon measures 10 cm as indicated in the figure below. Find its area. Use <m>\sin 51.43^\circ = 0.7818</m>.
            </p>
                <image>
                <latex-image label="regular-heptagon-example">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                    \def\R{4.5}
                    % Define the heptagon (scaled)
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:\R);
                    }
                    % Draw the heptagon
                    \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \draw (P0) -- (O) node[midway, above]{\small 10 cm};
                    \filldraw[black] (O) circle (2pt) node[above] {\small \textbf{O}};
                    % Label the vertices (offset from polygon)
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \node at ({360/7*\i}:{1.12*\R}) {$P_{\i}$};
                    }
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
           </image>
            </sidebyside>
           
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_y2ecej7k">
                There are 7 triangles since a heptagon has 7 sides.
                Area of Triangle <m>P_0OP_1 = \frac{1}{2} ab \, \sin \, 51.43^\circ </m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nw3qt7xx">
                <md>
                    <mrow>  \amp \triangle P_0OP_1 = \frac{1}{2}\times 10\times 10\, \sin \,51.43^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 100\, \text{cm}^2 \times \sin \, 51,43^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 100\, \text{cm}^2 \times 0.7818 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 39.0923 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lz94cit7">
                Therefore the total area 
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 7 \times 39.0923 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 273.65 \,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_7o0h6aif">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_xcddw3u3">
                Find the area of the regular heptagon given that its side measures <m>20</m> cm.
            </p>        
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_el120phq">
                <ol marker="Step 1:">
                    <li xml:id="auto_4l9ficy4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_r3brjmth">
                            Sketch the heptagon
                        </p>
                        <image>
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \def\R{4.5} % radius of circumcircle
                                    \foreach \i in {0,...,6} {
                                        \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:\R);
                                    }
                                    \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                                    \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\small O};
                                    \path (P0) -- (P1) node[midway, above] {\small 20 cm};
                                    \foreach \i in {0,...,6} {
                                        \node[font=\small] at (P\i) [above right] {$P_{\i}$};
                                    }
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0hirqnan">
                        <p xml:id="auto_lc2dc5zk">
                            Find the interior angle of the heptagon
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_rcu1o59p">
                            Let the interior angle be <m>\theta</m>, we can calculate it by
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_gyj77fxn">
                            <m>\theta = \frac{900}{7} \approx 128.57 ^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_iqw9s4hl">
                        <p xml:id="auto_d3f9vjzf">
                            Calculate the angle formed at the centre by the triangle extracted
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_0kxwi97i">
                            <m>\beta = \frac{360}{7} \approx 51.43^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_3eb8mlau">
                        <p xml:id="auto_umqic6pj">
                            Find the area of the triangle formed. Notice that the base angles of the triangle formed is half the interior angle <m>\theta</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_8bajls76">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times \text{Base} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 20 \times 10 \times \tan 64.285^\circ</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 100 \tan 64.285^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 207.65 \; \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_prjaqjz7">
                        <p xml:id="auto_gt5vkkfh">
                            The regular heptagon have <m>7</m> equal triangles, therefore its area is given by
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_r9nuvcfc">
                            <m> 7 \times 207.65 \; \text{cm}^2  = 1453.55 \; \text{cm}^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_kt0yl47q">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9okpgt8f">
            Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-heptagons">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heptagon-perimeter">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_cx1nd0aw">
                    A regular heptagon has a side length of <m>6 \text{cm}</m>. Calculate its perimeter.
                </p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="heptagon-perimeter-diagram">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                            \def\R{4.5}
                            % Define the heptagon (scaled)
                            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                                \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:\R);
                            }
                            % Draw the heptagon
                            \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                            % Draw one triangle
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P0) node[midway, above]{\small 6 cm};
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P1);
                            % Label the central angle (position scaled)
                            \node[font=\small] at (0.8,0.3) {$51.4^\circ$};
                            % Mark center point
                            \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\small O};
                            % Label the vertices
                            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                                \node[font=\small] at ({360/7*\i}:{1.12*\R}) {$P_{\i}$};
                            }
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_nq85rgeq">
                    Perimeter = <m>7 \times 6 = 42 \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heptagon-area-simple">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_yr7gwrc9">
                    A regular heptagon has a radius (distance from the center to a vertex) of <m>5 \text{cm}</m>. Draw the heptagon and calculate its area. Use <m>\sin 51.43^\circ = 0.7818</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="heptagon-area-simple-diagram">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                            \def\R{4.5}
                            % Define the heptagon (scaled)
                            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                                \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:\R);
                            }
                            % Draw the heptagon
                            \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                            % Draw one triangle
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P0) node[midway, above]{\small 5 cm};
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P1);
                            % Label the central angle (position scaled)
                            \node[font=\small] at (0.8, 0.3) {$51.4^\circ$};
                            % Mark center point
                            \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\small O};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_k75kb9n9">
                    Area of one triangle = <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 5 \times 5 \times \sin 51.43^\circ = 9.77 \text{cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_kqrk0tnt">
                    Total area = <m>7 \times 9.77 = 68.39 \text{cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heptagon-area-complex">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_a2rgd1gm">
                    A regular heptagon has a side length of <m>4 \text{cm}</m>. Draw the heptagon and calculate its area by dividing it into seven isosceles triangles and finding the area of one triangle. Use <m>\sin(\frac{360^\circ}{7}) \approx 0.4339</m>.
                </p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="heptagon-area-complex-diagram">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                            \def\R{4.5}
                            % Define the heptagon (scaled)
                            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                                \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:\R);
                            }
                            % Draw the heptagon
                            \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                            % Draw one triangle
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P0);
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P1);
                            % Label the central angle (position scaled)
                            \node[font=\small] at (0.8, 0.3) {$51.4^\circ$};
                            % Mark center point
                            \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\small O};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_r8cfb3am">
                    Area of one triangle = <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 4 \times 4 \times \sin(\frac{360^\circ}{7}) \approx 6.93 \text{ cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_wjciau3g">
                    Total area = <m>7 \times 6.93 \approx 48.51 \text{ cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heptagon-advanced">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_1xbjzsh8">
                    A regular heptagon is inscribed in a circle with a radius of <m>8 \text{cm}</m>. Calculate the area of the heptagon. Use <m>\sin 51.43^\circ = 0.7818</m>.
                </p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="heptagon-advanced-diagram">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                            \def\R{4.5}
                            % Define the heptagon (scaled)
                            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                                \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:\R);
                            }
                            % Draw the heptagon
                            \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                            % Draw one triangle
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P0);
                            \draw (0,0) -- (P1);
                            % Label the central angle (position scaled)
                            \node[font=\small] at (0.8, 0.3) {$51.4^\circ$};
                            % Mark center point
                            \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\small O};
                            % Label radius
                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (P0) node[midway, above]{\small 8 cm};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_aixuwdz1">
                    Area of the circle = <m>\pi r^2 = \pi \times 8^2 = 64\pi \text{ cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_f2fia01y">
                    Area of one triangle = <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 8 \times 8 \times \sin 51.43^\circ = 24.9792 \text{ cm}^2</m>,
                    so the heptagon area = <m>7 \times 24.9792 = 174.8544 \text{ cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xnv9sbfb">
                    Fraction of the circle occupied by the heptagon:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\dfrac{\text{Area of heptagon}}{\text{Area of circle}} = \dfrac{174.8544}{64\pi} \approx 0.8695</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_lsyg6x9t">
                    Exact expression (in terms of the central angle):
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\dfrac{\text{Area of heptagon}}{\text{Area of circle}} = \dfrac{7\left(\tfrac{1}{2}r^2\sin\tfrac{360^\circ}{7}\right)}{\pi r^2} = \dfrac{7}{2\pi}\sin\left(\tfrac{360^\circ}{7}\right)</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9ozjomu0">
                    As a percentage: <m>0.8695 \times 100\% \approx 86.95\%</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ahrdoj6o">
            <alert>Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8aelf27q">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_5pcluv05">
                    <p xml:id="auto_82tn647n">Provide pre-drawn circles with centre marked.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_z0of7n68">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nsshm81p">Use simpler numbers for radius lengths.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qzyrvqcj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_59gski0i">Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rr2gbhjl">
                    <p xml:id="auto_rtmtwhnr">Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_omsoo216">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0nosc5t7">Allow use of calculators.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_oeeounwq">
            <alert>On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pys1txo2">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_sxv6t3vb">
                    <p xml:id="auto_1i3nx1jg">Encourage students to draw their own heptagons from word problems.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bbbr1t2b">
                    <p xml:id="auto_o200n630">Ask students to explain which formula they chose and why.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_k36g04c2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dbc2zgve">Provide mixed practice with both finding area and finding missing dimensions.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_274zbkd0">
            <alert>Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ardsqhw5">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_96ifc60k">
                    <p xml:id="auto_htnq83av">Challenge students to derive the area formula themselves using the concept of dividing into triangles.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_26a7nzgf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_yxoxnlox">Explore real-world applications: architecture, coin design, logo design.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7x0rgpoj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ntl9b9l1">Investigate the relationship between the area of a heptagon and other regular polygons.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hu0qsdhn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ytdc3dd2">Apply trigonometry to find all angles and side lengths when given only the radius.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9uong1r9">
            <alert>Extension Activity — Real-World Application:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8r09odj2">
            Students work in groups to design a heptagon-shaped structure (coin, logo, architectural feature, garden) and calculate its area. Tasks include:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_avt96adz">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_uk9fof31">
                    <p xml:id="auto_69e7karj">Choose a real-world application that uses heptagon shapes.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_u9sp254l">
                    <p xml:id="auto_k4vf574l">Draw the heptagon on graph paper with appropriate dimensions.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_j287col7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_1tmciv04">Calculate the area using the triangle method.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_odihclk3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dfe0l6ft">Present findings to the class, explaining design choices and calculations.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx" />

</subsubsection>